//Luna code example
//TODO:While testing parser, make sure it can handle trailing commas in function calls, struct literals, tuples, arrays, maps, and so on. 
//Important nuiences:-
// ---- Variadic & $loop generalization ----
// *args and **kwargs are NOT compile-time values. Their elements are evaluated at runtime.
// However, $loop still works on them because $loop operates on the *structure* of the pack,
// which IS known at compile time (the argument count and types). The compiler statically
// unrolls the loop; only the values inside each iteration are runtime.
//
// This is not special-cased for variadics. $loop generalizes to anything whose shape is
// known at compile time but whose values may not be:
//   - Tuples      : $loop $v : my_tuple   -> iterates over each element by position
//   - Structs     : $loop $v : my_struct  -> iterates over each field by declaration order
//   - *args/**kwargs : same idea, pack structure is CT, values are RT
//
// The distinction between CT-value and RT-value variadics:
//   $loop $v : $args  ->  CT pack, CT values  (*$args or **$kwargs, values must be constexpr)
//   $loop $v : args   ->  CT pack, RT values  (*args or **kwargs,   values evaluated at runtime)
//
// In both cases the loop is fully unrolled at compile time. The difference is only
// whether the compiler can use the values for CT decisions (e.g. inside $when).

// There is a concept of sumtype and interface but no seperate concept of union. Sure we need it for c interop but Luna itself doesnt need it other than that
// So in C if a function takes in union or returns a union then we can  just convert it to a struct. Yes the user has to write  a bit of extra code on C side
// But keeps luna clean from clutter

// Note:-In thread and task, the body takes in every variable in scope by reference and no u cant change that. Same for the body of coalesing operators

//Note:- A function and method may have the same name irrespective of type.
//You can pass function as parameter to other function and method but you cant pass method as parameter to other function or method. 
//You can have multiple methods with the same name as long as their receiver or atleast one argument type is different. 
//You can have multiple functions with the same name as long as their parameter types are different.

//!! :- Means error coalescing operator. It is used to handle errors in a concise way. It is similar to null coalescing operator but for errors. 
//      It allows you to provide a default value in case of error or code block to run
//?? :- Means null coalescing operator. It is used to handle optional values in a concise way. It allows you to provide a default value in case of None or code block to run
//Let's say you do ``var := expr !! code_body`` or ``var := expr ?? code_body`` and  code body doesnt give any value then the cody body must exit from that scope
//Doesnt matter how it exits the scope(Maybe a break if in loop or a return). But it must exit the scope. 
//This is because if code body doesnt give any value then the whole expr !! code_body or expr ?? code_body will not have any value and it will be a compile error. 
//So to avoid that we enforce that code body must exit the scope if it doesnt give any value.
// Actually for the above 2, I will think in future if the code should implecitely exit the scope or the programmer should do it and throw error if programmer forgets
// If u do expr! and expr gives an error then it will throw the error and exit the program. So use !! if you want to handle the error and not exit the program.
// If u do expr? then syntax error because that is not allowed cuz dont make sense

/*
has_value() method for both ?T and !T . 

Also stuff like == and != Work on them without null/error coalescing and work as u would expect but <,> etc don't for obvious reason
*/
/*
In most programming languages we have the following logical and bitwise operators:
Logical (`&&`, `||`): These short-circuit. If the first part of an `if` statement fails, the second part never runs. This prevents crashes (e.g., checking `if (obj != null && obj.prop)`) and saves performance.
Bitwise (`&`, `|`): These are eager. They evaluate both sides every time and work on the binary bits of numbers (e.g., `5 & 3` results in `1`).

But here we only have `&` and `|`
If a|b or a&b is used in a boolean context then it behaves like logical operator and short-circuits. 
If used in a non-boolean context then it behaves like bitwise operator and evaluates both sides every time. 
This is a unique design choice that simplifies the language by having only one set of operators for both logical and bitwise operations, while still providing 
the benefits of short-circuiting in boolean contexts.
*/
// Note a..b..c is equivalent to Range(a,b,c) and returns an iter. Not unique to loops. U can even do x := a..b..c


/*
For simd type <elem_type, lanes>, the lanes must be an integer or a compile time variable
What I mean by only compile time variable is that we can have the following
<f32,4>,<f32,$lanes>
But not <f32, 2+2> or <f32, $some_func()>, <f32, $some_var + 1> and so on. 
This is just done for making the parser simpler without reducing features 
*/
